Method 1.  Apply \diff{}{x} to both sides of
.
This gives

y''(x)=3y(x)^2\,y''(x)+6y(x)\,y'(x)^2+2y'(x)+x\,y''(x)+6x

We can now solve for y''(x), giving

y''(x) = \frac{6x+2y'(x)+6y(x)y'(x)^2}{1-x-3y(x)^2}

Then we can substitute in , giving


y''(x) &= 2\frac{3x+ \frac{y(x)+3x^2}{1-x-3y(x)^2}
              +3y(x) \big(\frac{y(x)+3x^2}{1-x-3y(x)^2}\big)^2}
         {1-x-3y(x)^2}

&= 2\frac{3x{[1-x-3y(x)^2]}^2+ [y(x)+3x^2][1-x-3y(x)^2]
              +3y(x) {[y(x)+3x^2]}^2}{{[1-x-3y(x)^2]}^3}

Remark 2. Even though we cannot solve y=y^3+xy+x^3 explicitly for y(x), for general x, it is sometimes possible to solve equations like this for some special values of x. In fact, we saw in Example that when x=1, the given equation reduces to y(1)=y(1)^3+1\cdot y(1)+1^3, or y(1)^3=-1, which we can solve to get y(1)=-1. Substituting into , as we did in Example gives
y'(1) = \frac{-1+3}{1-1-3(-1)^2} = -\frac{2}{3}
and substituting into gives
y''(1) = \frac{6+2\big(-\frac{2}{3}\big)+6(-1)\big(-\frac{2}{3}\big)^2} {1-1-3(-1)^2} =\frac{6-\frac{4}{3}-\frac{8}{3}}{-3} = -\frac{2}{3}
(It's a fluke that, in this example, y'(1) and y''(1) happen to be equal.) So we now know that, even though we can't solve y=y^3+xy+x^3 explicitly for y(x), the graph of the solution passes through (1,-1) and has slope -\frac{2}{3} (i.e. is sloping downwards by between 30^\circ and 45^\circ) there and, furthermore, the slope of the graph decreases as x increases through x=1.
